	<section>
		<h2>ü§ù Setting Up Accountability Partners</h2>

		<h3>Choosing the Right Accountability Partner</h3>
		<p>Your accountability partner should be:</p>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Trustworthy:</strong> Someone you respect who won't judge</li>
			<li><strong>Committed:</strong> Willing to review reports and follow up</li>
			<li><strong>Same situation:</strong> Understanding your struggles (spouse, friend with similar goals, mentor)</li>
			<li><strong>Available:</strong> Responsive to alerts and reports</li>
			<li><strong>Encouraging:</strong> Supportive, not condemning</li>
		</ul>

		<h3>Best Accountability Partner Options</h3>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Spouse:</strong> Natural for married individuals</li>
			<li><strong>Close friend:</strong> Someone facing similar challenges</li>
			<li><strong>Mentor/pastor:</strong> Spiritual guidance</li>
			<li><strong>Accountability group:</strong> Multiple people supporting each other</li>
			<li><strong>Therapist/counselor:</strong> Professional support for addiction</li>
		</ul>

		<div class="alert alert-warning">
			<strong>Important:</strong> Don't choose someone who will enable bad behavior or ignore reports. The partner must be willing to have difficult conversations when needed.
		</div>

		<h3>Setting Expectations</h3>
		<ul>
			<li>How often will you review reports together?</li>
			<li>What constitutes a concerning pattern?</li>
			<li>How will partner respond to flagged content?</li>
			<li>What if reports are ignored or disabled?</li>
			<li>Regular check-ins beyond just reports</li>
		</ul>
	</section>

